<Document>
<name>Seward Highway</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Seward Highway</h2><p><i>Alaska, USA · AK-1/AK-9, Anchorage to Seward</i></p><p><b>All-American Road from city to glacier — Turnagain Arm, beluga whales, bore tides, Kenai Peninsula.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>182 km (113 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>3 hrs no stops</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>May–September (winter drivable but hazardous)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Moose on road (a real fatal-collision risk), winter avalanches, fog, distracted-driver crashes</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>244</td></tr></table><hr><p>An All-American Road for good reason — you drive between the Chugach Mountains and the tide-rocking Turnagain Arm, watch belugas surface, then climb past glaciers into the Kenai Peninsula. Watch for Dall sheep on the cliffs above the road; they are sometimes painted onto the rock by the angle of light. Time the bore tide if you can — Turnagain has the second-largest tidal range in North America, and the incoming tide can travel as a single 2 m wave. End in Seward, gateway to Kenai Fjords NP and one of the most spectacular small towns on the continent. Side-trip to Exit Glacier is nearly free.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Potter Marsh</b> — 1.5 km boardwalk over a tidal marsh. Migratory birds in spring/fall; salmon spawning visible from boardwalk in late summer.</li><li><b>Beluga Point</b> — Belugas surface here July–August on the incoming tide. Scopes provided. Dall sheep on the cliffs above the parking lot.</li><li><b>Bird Point</b> — Best viewing platform for the Turnagain Arm bore tide. Tide tables posted; the wave arrives 2 hours after Anchorage low tide.</li><li><b>Alyeska tram</b> — Tram up Mount Alyeska to glacier-and-Sound views; restaurant at the top operating year-round.</li><li><b>Portage Glacier</b> — Short spur road; visitor center with face-on glacier view (the glacier itself has retreated out of sight, but boat tours go to it).</li><li><b>Exit Glacier (Seward)</b> — Drive up to within walking distance of an actively calving glacier. Markers along the road show its 1815, 1899, 1951... retreat.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
